{"title_page": "Kevin Johnson (executive)", "text_new": "{{other people|Kevin Johnson}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kevin Johnson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1960|10|09}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gig Harbor, Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Leading [[Starbucks]] as chief executive\n| alma_mater         = [[New Mexico State University]]\n| occupation         = Business executive\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]], U.S.\n| title              = President and CEO, Starbucks\n| term               = 2017\u2013present\n| predecessor        = [[Howard Schultz]]\n| successor          = \n| spouse             = \n| website            = {{URL|https://stories.starbucks.com/leadership/kevin-johnson/|Starbucks}}\n}}\n\n'''Kevin R. Johnson''' (born October 9, 1960) is an American businessman and [[software engineer]] who has been the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Starbucks Coffee Company]] since 2017. Succeeding [[Howard Schultz|Howard Shultz]] as CEO, Johnson previously served as the company's president and chief operating officer from 2015 to 2017. He served on  <!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.-->\n\nBorn in [[Gig Harbor, Washington]], Johnson was raised in [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]]. He graduated from [[New Mexico State University]] in 1981 before embarking on a career in software development. Johnson first worked at a systems engineer at [[IBM]] during the late-1980s, before moving to [[Microsoft]] in 1992 to working in global technical support. After one of his earliest clients, Starbucks, needed [[Wireless|wireless internet]] in their stores, Johnson first met Schultz. Working closely with Microsoft CEO [[Steve Ballmer|Steve Balmer]] and founder [[Bill Gates]], Johnson oversaw strategy for Microsoft and the firm's online search and advertising strategy. Johnson left Microsoft during the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2007-08 financial crisis]] to serve as chief executive of [[Juniper Networks]] from September 2008 to January 2014.\n\nJohnson first joined Starbucks in September 2009 as a board member after which Schultz asked him to take a greater role at the firm. He was subsequently appointed chief operating officer for two years before becoming chief executive. Under his tenure, Starbucks has streamlined its core business, managed corporate programs to address [[Racism in the United States|racial inequality in the U.S.]], and revamped its product suite [[Horizontal integration|horizontally]], particularly in espresso machine manufacturing and technological innovation. <!--Leave space for {{TOC}}.-->\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn on October 9, 1960 in [[Gig Harbor, Washington]],<ref name=Jargon>{{cite news |last1=Jargon |first1=Julie |title=New Starbucks CEO Sees Growth in Suburbs, Midwest and Lunch, The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-ceo-on-where-starbucks-sees-growth-suburbs-midwest-lunch-1491192060 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |date=3 April 2017}}</ref> Johnson later moved to and was raised in [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]] with his siblings. His mother, Carol, was a pediatric nurse at the Children's Clinic of Los Alamos, while his father Jim worked at [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] as a [[theoretical physicist]].<ref name=\"Starbucks2\">{{cite web |title=Tech Leader Kevin Johnson Begins New Role as Starbucks President and COO |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2015/tech-leader-kevin-johnson-begins-new-role-as-starbucks-president-and-coo/|date=2 March 2015|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=LAdaily>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=Marie |title=Los Alamos High School Graduate Kevin Johnson Becomes CEO Of Starbucks |url=https://www.ladailypost.com/content/los-alamos-high-school-graduate-kevin-johnson-becomes-ceo-starbucks-april-3 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=LA Daily Post |date=10 November 2019}}</ref> Johnson graduated from [[Los Alamos High School]] in 1978.<ref name=LAdaily/> He went on to graduate from [[New Mexico State University]] (NMSU) in 1981, with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in business administration.<ref name=KOMO>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson to receive honorary degree |url=https://komonews.com/news/business/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson-to-receive-honorary-degree |website=komonews.com |publisher=KOMO News |accessdate=10 November 2019 |date=11 May 2017}}</ref> He received an honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] from NMSU in 2017.<ref name=\"Stolder\">{{cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2017/kevin-johnson-honorary-doctorate/|title=Kevin Johnson Returns to New Mexico State to Receive Honorary Doctorate|last1=Stolder|first1=Steve|date=May 15, 2017|publisher=Starbucks|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=KOMO/>\n\n==Career==\n===IBM and Microsoft===\nJohnson began his career as a [[software engineer]] and became a systems engineer at [[IBM]], in 1986, working in the company's systems integration and consulting business unit.<ref name=Ward>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/04/03/3-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson.html|title=3 ways CEO Kevin Johnson's leadership style could shape Starbucks|last=Ward|first=Marguerite|date=2017-04-03|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> At IBM he also worked as a software developer in the petroleum and financial services industries.<ref name=\"CNET\">{{cite news |last1=Fried |first1=Ina |title=Kevin Johnson to leave Microsoft for Juniper |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/kevin-johnson-to-leave-microsoft-for-juniper/ |accessdate=16 November 2019 |agency=CNET |publisher=CBS |date=24 July 2008}}</ref> Johnson joined Microsoft in 1992, working in global technical support<ref name=\"ST-Tu\"/><ref name=\"LinkedIn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/kevjohns|title=Kevin Johnson|website=Linkedin|accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> and, later, sales and marketing.<ref name=\"Gilbert\">{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Alorie|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/sizing-up-microsofts-new-windows-chief/|title=Sizing up Microsoft's new Windows chief|date=21 September 2005|accessdate=12 November 2019|publisher=CNET}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-9998192-56.html|title=Kevin Johnson to leave Microsoft for Juniper|date=July 23, 2008|publisher=CNET NEWS|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011195003/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-9998192-56.html|archive-date=October 11, 2008|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> In 2001, he led the rollout of Microsoft wireless internet in Starbucks stores,<ref name=\"Starbucks3\" /><ref name=Garnick/> which is when he met and began working with Starbucks founder Howard Schultz.<ref name=Garnick/> In 2003, Johnson was appointed group vice president of Microsoft's worldwide sales, marketing and services group.<ref name=\"cnet2\"/> As head of worldwide sales, the company's top sales post, he \"re-engineered field sales and realigned subsidiary operations\" in around 80 countries.<ref name=Gilbert/> On September 30, 2005 he was appointed co-president of Microsoft's newly created Platforms division, assuming sole responsibility after co-president Jim Allchin retired in 2006, giving Johnson responsibility over [[Windows Live]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] operating systems, [[online advertising]], search functions,<ref name=\"MSNBC\" /> servers, tools, and [[MSN]] online.<ref name=\"AP/NYT\">{{cite news |title=Microsoft Announces Major Reorganization |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/technology/microsoft-announces-major-reorganization.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=The New York Times |date=September 20, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet2\" /> Johnson oversaw $20 billion out of Microsoft's $56 billion in revenue,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Holen |first1=Endre |title=My transition story |journal=McKinsey Quarterly |date=June 2010 |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/featured-insights/leadership/my-transition-story |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> spearheading its \"revamped online search and advertising strategy,\" regarded as crucial to competing with Google's online search tools.<ref name=\"CNET\" /> In 2006, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' named Johnson fourth on a list of \"Rising Stars\" in the technology industry.<ref name=\"Colvin\">{{cite news |last1=Colvin |first1=Geoffrey |title=The war for top talent |url=https://archive.fortune.com/2006/01/23/magazines/fortune/starintroduction_fortune_060206/index.htm |accessdate=20 November 2019 |publisher=Fortune |date=January 25, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn the Senior Leadership Team, Johnson became one of six executives along with Steve Ballmer and Bill Gates who oversaw strategy for Microsoft.<ref name=Gilbert/> Overseeing the release of Windows Vista in 2006 and 2007, in 2007 Johnson led Microsoft's acquisition of the online advertising company aQuantive for $6 billion.<ref name=MSNBC/> In 2008, he was a key figure in negotiations between Yahoo and Microsoft,<ref name=MSNBC/> with Microsoft ultimately withdrawing an acquisition offer. He resigned from Microsoft in July 2008.<ref name=\"MSNBC\" /><ref name=\"cnet2\"/>\n\n===Juniper===\nIn September 2008, Johnson became CEO of [[Juniper Networks]], in [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/windows/operatingsystems/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=209600497 |title=Microsoft Windows Exec Kevin Johnson Jumps To Juniper |date=2008-07-24 |publisher=InformationWeek |accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref><ref name=Network>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/news/2008/072508-juniper-ceo.html |title=Juniper CEO: Timing right to step aside |date=2008-07-25 |publisher=Network World |accessdate=2009-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124162146/http://www.networkworld.com/news/2008/072508-juniper-ceo.html |archivedate=2009-01-24 }}</ref><ref name=Sutton>{{cite web|url=http://www.itp.net/news/525861-kevin-johnson-signed-as-new-juniper-ceo|title=Kevin Johnson signed as new Juniper CEO |date=2008-07-25|publisher=ITP.Net|accessdate=2009-02-03|author=Sutton, Mark}}</ref><ref name=Lai>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9110561 |title=Update: Windows and online chief to leave Microsoft in wake of Yahoo tussle |date=2008-07-23 |publisher=Computerworld |accessdate=2009-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731170859/http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9110561 |archivedate=2008-07-31 |author=Lai, Eric}}</ref> In a statement announcing Johnson's departure from Microsoft to serve as CEO of Juniper, [[Steve Ballmer]], CEO, Microsoft, praised Johnson's contribution to the company.<ref name=MSNBC>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25823251/ns/business-us_business/t/top-online-windows-exec-depart-microsoft/#.W-XmDnpKhTY|title=Top online, Windows exec to depart Microsoft|date=2008-07-24|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> In July 2013, Juniper Networks announced that Johnson would step down as CEO and planned to retire. He continued to serve as CEO while a search for a new CEO was conducted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crn.com/news/networking/240158806/juniper-ceo-johnson-out-amid-q2-earnings.htm|title=Juniper CEO Johnson Out Amid Q2 Earnings|last=Bent|first=Kristin|work=CRN|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In January 2014, Johnson was succeeded as Juniper CEO by [[Shaygan Kheradpir]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Juniper Networks gets new CEO|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24516152/juniper-networks-gets-new-ceo-shaygan-kheradpir|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=2014-02-20}}</ref>\n\n===Starbucks===\n[[File:Starbuckscenter.jpg|thumb|298x298px|Johnson first joined Starbucks in 2009, serving as president and [[Chief operating officer|COO]] from 2015 to 2017. Following the resignation of [[Howard Schultz]], Johnson was appointed his successor; he has served as CEO since 2017.]]\nJohnson became president and COO of Starbucks in March 2015, remaining on its board.<ref name=LAdaily/><ref name=KOMO/> He had oversight of global operations, including the [[supply chain]] and technology supporting 21,000 stores in 66 countries.<ref name=Starbucks2/> He also oversaw online platforms<ref name=CNBC>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/30/one-year-into-starbucks-top-job-ceo-kevin-johnson-still-has-a-lot-to-prove.html|title=One year into Starbucks' top job, CEO Kevin Johnson still has a lot to prove|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=2018-03-30|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> and worked with Schultz on a five-year strategic plan for the company, released in December 2016.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Kate|title=Starbucks' new CEO tells us he'll never be Howard Schultz halehluijah- and that's great news for the brand|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/interview-with-starbucks-new-ceo-kevin-johnson-2017-4|website=Business Insider|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=2017-04-11|date=2017-04-03}}</ref> In December 2016 it was announced that [[Howard Schultz]] would step down as CEO of Starbucks, and  in April 2017 that he had personally recruited Johnson to be his successor.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGrath|first1=Maggie|title=Howard Schultz Stepping Down As Starbucks CEO|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maggiemcgrath/2016/12/01/howard-schultz-stepping-down-as-starbucks-ceo/ |website=Forbes|accessdate=2017-04-11|date=2016-12-01}}</ref> On April 3, 2017,<ref name=\"Starbucks2\" /> Johnson became the fourth CEO in Starbucks history,<ref name=\"Garnick\">{{cite news |last1=Garnick |first1=Coral |title=Starbucks expands parental leave in fight to recruit and retain workers |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2017/01/19/starbucks-parental-leave-benefits-improvement.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=Puget Sound Business Journal |date=29 January 2017}}</ref> also remaining president.<ref name=\"Tu\">{{cite news| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/starbucks/new-starbucks-ceo-aims-to-build-company-that-will-last-a-century/|title=New Starbucks CEO aims to build company that will last a century| publisher=The Seattle Times|date=3 April 2017|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> By 2018, he had implemented a number of changes, including the rollout of mobile ordering and pickup, and a global distribution deal with Nestle.<ref name=\"Gelles\">{{cite news |last1=Gelles |first1=David |title=The C.E.O. of Starbucks Isn\u2019t Leaving. Only Howard Schultz Is. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/17/business/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson.html |date=17 June 2019|accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite news |last1=Edgecliffe-Johnson |first1=Andrew |title=Starbucks' Kevin Johnson: taking on a founder's brand |url=https://www.ft.com/content/62e2323c-f927-11e8-af46-2022a0b02a6c |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=The Financial Times |date=9 December 2018}}</ref> For $7.15 billion, Nestle agreed to market Starbucks products outside of Starbucks stores in countries such as the US and China,<ref name=\"FT\" /> as well as use Starbucks coffee in [[Nespresso]] and [[Nescafe]] products.<ref>{{cite news |title=Starbucks and Nestl\u00e9 Form Global Coffee Alliance to Elevate and Expand Consumer Packaged Goods |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/press/2018/starbucks-and-nestle-form-global-coffee-alliance/ |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=Starbucks |date=7 May 2018}}</ref> Under Johnson, Starbucks acquired 100 percent of its East China joint venture for $1.3 billion. He also closed Teavana stores and the e-commerce unit, and sold [[Tazo]] to [[Unilever]] for $384 million.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> Analyst commentary on his first year was mixed. While he received criticism for weak sales in the United States, he was praised by ''CNBC'' for growth in China<ref name=\"CNBC\" /> and well-received by ''Bloomberg'' and ''The New York Times''.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> Media also credited Johnson with a 15 percent stock value increase between 2017 and November 2018,<ref name=\"Jargon\" /> noted as \"not far from an all-time high.\"<ref name=\"LaMonica\">{{cite news |last1=LaMonica |first1=Paul R. |title=Starbucks is doing better than ever after Howard Schultz |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/investing/starbucks-stock-kevin-johnson/index.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=CNN Business |date=30 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, advocates petitioned Johnson to include baristas in Starbucks paid parental leave policy,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boushey |first1=Heather|last2=Bethell|first2=Katie |title=Everyone should have a shot at paid family leave\" |url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/04/opinions/paid-family-leave-for-all-boushey-bethell/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garnick |first1=Coral |title=Starbucks expands parental leave in fight to recruit and retain workers |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2017/01/19/starbucks-parental-leave-benefits-improvement.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=Puget Sound Business Journal |date=29 January 2017}}</ref> and Johnson announced an expanded policy in 2018.<ref name=\"CNBC\" />\n\nIn May 2018, two Black men, who were waiting for a business associate to arrive, were arrested for trespassing in a Philadelphia Starbucks, resulting in public protests and accusations of [[racial profiling]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Emily |first1=Stewart |title=Two black men were arrested in a Philadelphia Starbucks for doing nothing |url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2018/4/14/17238494/what-happened-at-starbucks-black-men-arrested-philadelphia |website=Vox |accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Prudy\" /><ref name=\"Stoonic\" /> Describing the incident as \"reprehensible\"<ref name=\"Stoonic\" /> and apologizing personally on ''Good Morning America'', Johnson met with the victims<ref name=\"Meyer\">{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Ziati |title=Starbucks CEO vows to learn from 'mistake' in racial incident |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2018/04/26/starbucks-ceo-apologizes-mistake-racial-incident/554597002/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=USA Today |date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> and the Philadelphia police commissioner to arrange a settlement.<ref name=\"Prudy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/prudygourguechon/2018/05/06/the-psychology-of-apology-how-did-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson-do/#6313fd2ac8d2|title=The Psychology Of Apology: How Did Starbucks' CEO Kevin Johnson Do?|first=Prudy|last=Gourguechon|publisher=|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref> Johnson was \"widely praised\" then for also closing all United States stores for racial-bias training.<ref name=\"LaMonica\" /><ref name=\"Prudy\" /><ref name=\"Meyer\" /><ref name=\"Olsen\">{{cite news |last1=Olsen |title=Starbucks to close stores for an afternoon for bias training, |url=https://www.lamonitor.com/content/starbucks-close-stores-afternoon-bias-training |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=Los Angeles Monitor |date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Pitts\">{{cite news |last1=Pitts |first1=Loenard |title=A standing ovation for the Starbucks CEO who confronted the truth about racism in America |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/leonard-pitts-jr/article209467289.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=Miami Herald |date=April 20, 2018}}</ref> and mandating anti-[[bias]] training for management<ref name=\"Stoonic\" /><ref name=\"Meyer\" /> and new hires.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> In 2018, Johnson opened the Tryer Center, a Seattle research laboratory, to test new product and equipment ideas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=La Roche |first1=Julia |title=How tech-savvy Kevin Johnson is creating 'the next generation' of Starbucks |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/starbucks-kevin-johnson-explains-tech-savvy-approach-161109308.html |publisher=Yahoo! finance |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Under Johnson, in 2018 and 2019, the company began developing biodegradable lids, straws, and cups,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winer-Bronner|first1=Danielle |title=Starbucks is eliminating plastic straws from all stores |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/09/news/companies/starbucks-plastic-straws/index.html |publisher=The Financial Times |date=9 July 2018|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> and partnered with UberEATS and Alibaba to deliver in the United States and China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Amelia |title=Starbucks ramps up US delivery with UberEats as Chinese delivery booms |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/26/starbucks-ramps-up-us-delivery-with-ubereats-as-chinese-delivery-booms.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=CNBC}}</ref> ''The Financial Times'' reported, in 2018, that \"colleagues credit [Johnson's] tech background with helping Starbucks outpace other retailers in mobile ordering and payments.\"<ref name=\"FT\" /> He was named one of Seattle\u2019s Most Influential People of 2018 by ''Seattle Magazine'' for partnering Starbucks and Mary's Place, along with other initiatives to support homeless families.<ref name=\"Stoonic\">{{cite journal |last1=Stoonic |first1=Niki |title=Seattle\u2019s Most Influential People 2018: Starbucks CEO, Kevin Johnson |url=https://www.seattlemag.com/news-and-features/seattles-most-influential-people-2018-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson |accessdate=11 November 2019 |journal=Seattle Magazine |issue=November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, it was reported that Johnson was scaling down several of Schultz's initiatives from two years prior, including testing of Starbucks Reserve Roastery cafes. According to ''The Wall Street Journal'', that \"discipline\" had also resulted in slowed store growth in the United States, and that Johnson was \"working to improve customer service, pushing the company to develop more innovative beverages and expanding its reach in China.\"<ref name=\"Jargon\" /> Under Johnson, Starbucks shares had risen 79 percent by August 2019, and Johnson pledged to return $25 billion to shareholders by 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cannivet |first1=Michael |title=Starbucks' Big Stock Buyback Limits Future Upside |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelcannivet/2019/08/29/starbucks-big-stock-buyback-limits-future-upside/#23e9ba227047 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |publisher=Forbes |date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government work ==\nIn 2008, Johnson was appointed by [[George W. Bush]] to the National Security Telecommunications Advisory Committee (NSTAC),<ref name=\"NSTAC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/NSTAC%20Members%20-%20JohnsonK%20(Juniper%20Networks)_0.pdf|title=Committee Member Biography The President\u2019s National Security Telecommunications Advisory Committee|date=March 25, 2010|accessdate=13 November 2019|publisher=Department of Homeland Security}}</ref> where he served under Bush and [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"LAdaily\" /> As chairman of the cybersecurity committee, Johnson was tasked with proposing methods to deal with a cyber security attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nextgov.com/cybersecurity/2009/05/experts-make-push-for-cybersecurity-coordination-center/43887/|title=Experts make push for cybersecurity coordination center|last1=Noyes|first1=Andrew|date=May 22, 2009|website=Nextgov.com|publisher=Atlantic Media Co.|accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson and his wife, June, have two sons<ref name=\"ST-Tu\">{{cite news |last1=Tu |first1=Janet |title=New Starbucks CEO aims to build company that will last a century |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/starbucks/new-starbucks-ceo-aims-to-build-company-that-will-last-a-century/ |accessdate=14 November 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=LAdaily/> and reside in [[Medina, Washington|Medina]] and [[Bellevue, Washington]].<ref name=\"Starbucks3\">{{cite web |title=A Conversation with New Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2017/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson/ |publisher=Starbucks |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ST-Tu\"/> Around 2012 Johnson temporarily retired from business to focus on his health, having previously diagnosed with a treatable cancer.<ref name=Starbucks3/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40509007/the-health-scare-that-revitalized-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson |title=The Health Scare That Revitalized Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson|website=Fastcompany.com |publisher=Fast Company |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> Johnson is active in basketball, boating, golfing, skiing, and hiking.<ref name=\"ST-Tu\" /><ref name=Garnick/> A sports fan, Johnson cites writings by basketball coach [[John Wooden]] as a personal influence.<ref name=Starbucks3/>\n\nJohnson has served as an advisor to [[Catalyst (nonprofit organization)|Catalyst]], an organization dedicated to women's career advancement; is a founding board member of the [[nonprofit organization]] NPower; and supports Youth Eastside Services, and the No Child Sleeps Outside campaign.<ref name=\"ST-Tu\" /><ref name=\"Starbucks2\" /><ref name=\"Starbucks2\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of chief executive officers]]\n*[[List of New Mexico State University people|List of New Mexico State University alumni]]\n*[[Development of Windows Vista]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Juniper Networks}}\n{{Starbucks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Kevin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]] \n[[Category:Juniper Networks]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:People associated with networking industry]]\n[[Category:Directors of Starbucks]]\n[[Category:New Mexico State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Starbucks people]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Kevin Johnson}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kevin Johnson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1960|10|09}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gig Harbor, Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Leading [[Starbucks]] as chief executive\n| alma_mater         = [[New Mexico State University]]\n| occupation         = Business executive\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]], U.S.\n| title              = President and CEO, Starbucks\n| term               = 2017\u2013present\n| predecessor        = [[Howard Schultz]]\n| successor          = \n| spouse             = \n| website            = {{URL|https://stories.starbucks.com/leadership/kevin-johnson/|Starbucks}}\n}}\n\n'''Kevin R. Johnson''' (born October 9, 1960) is an American businessman and [[software engineer]] who has been as the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Starbucks Coffee Company]] since 2017. Succeeding [[Howard Schultz|Howard Shultz]] as CEO, Johnson previously served as the company's president and chief operating officer from 2015 to 2017. He served on  <!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.-->\n\nBorn in [[Gig Harbor, Washington]], Johnson was raised in [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]]. He graduated from [[New Mexico State University]] in 1981 before embarking on a career in software development. Johnson first worked at a systems engineer at [[IBM]] during the late-1980s, before moving to [[Microsoft]] in 1992 to working in global technical support. After one of his earliest clients, Starbucks, needed [[Wireless|wireless internet]] in their stores, Johnson first met Schultz. Working closely with Microsoft CEO [[Steve Ballmer|Steve Balmer]] and founder [[Bill Gates]], Johnson oversaw strategy for Microsoft and the firm's online search and advertising strategy. Johnson left Microsoft during the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2007-08 financial crisis]] to serve as chief executive of [[Juniper Networks]] from September 2008 to January 2014.\n\nJohnson first joined Starbucks in September 2009 as a board member after which Schultz asked him to take a greater role at the firm. He was subsequently appointed chief operating officer for two years before becoming chief executive. Under his tenure, Starbucks has streamlined its core business, managed corporate programs to address [[Racism in the United States|racial inequality in the U.S.]], and revamped its product suite [[Horizontal integration|horizontally]], particularly in espresso machine manufacturing and technological innovation. <!--Leave space for {{TOC}}.-->\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn on October 9, 1960 in [[Gig Harbor, Washington]],<ref name=Jargon>{{cite news |last1=Jargon |first1=Julie |title=New Starbucks CEO Sees Growth in Suburbs, Midwest and Lunch, The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-ceo-on-where-starbucks-sees-growth-suburbs-midwest-lunch-1491192060 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |date=3 April 2017}}</ref> Johnson later moved to and was raised in [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]] with his siblings. His mother, Carol, was a pediatric nurse at the Children's Clinic of Los Alamos, while his father Jim worked at [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] as a [[theoretical physicist]].<ref name=\"Starbucks2\">{{cite web |title=Tech Leader Kevin Johnson Begins New Role as Starbucks President and COO |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2015/tech-leader-kevin-johnson-begins-new-role-as-starbucks-president-and-coo/|date=2 March 2015|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=LAdaily>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=Marie |title=Los Alamos High School Graduate Kevin Johnson Becomes CEO Of Starbucks |url=https://www.ladailypost.com/content/los-alamos-high-school-graduate-kevin-johnson-becomes-ceo-starbucks-april-3 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=LA Daily Post |date=10 November 2019}}</ref> Johnson graduated from [[Los Alamos High School]] in 1978.<ref name=LAdaily/> He went on to graduate from [[New Mexico State University]] (NMSU) in 1981, with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in business administration.<ref name=KOMO>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson to receive honorary degree |url=https://komonews.com/news/business/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson-to-receive-honorary-degree |website=komonews.com |publisher=KOMO News |accessdate=10 November 2019 |date=11 May 2017}}</ref> He received an honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] from NMSU in 2017.<ref name=\"Stolder\">{{cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2017/kevin-johnson-honorary-doctorate/|title=Kevin Johnson Returns to New Mexico State to Receive Honorary Doctorate|last1=Stolder|first1=Steve|date=May 15, 2017|publisher=Starbucks|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=KOMO/>\n\n==Career==\n===IBM and Microsoft===\nJohnson began his career as a [[software engineer]] and became a systems engineer at [[IBM]], in 1986, working in the company's systems integration and consulting business unit.<ref name=Ward>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/04/03/3-things-you-need-to-know-about-new-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson.html|title=3 ways CEO Kevin Johnson's leadership style could shape Starbucks|last=Ward|first=Marguerite|date=2017-04-03|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> At IBM he also worked as a software developer in the petroleum and financial services industries.<ref name=\"CNET\">{{cite news |last1=Fried |first1=Ina |title=Kevin Johnson to leave Microsoft for Juniper |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/kevin-johnson-to-leave-microsoft-for-juniper/ |accessdate=16 November 2019 |agency=CNET |publisher=CBS |date=24 July 2008}}</ref> Johnson joined Microsoft in 1992, working in global technical support<ref name=\"ST-Tu\"/><ref name=\"LinkedIn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/kevjohns|title=Kevin Johnson|website=Linkedin|accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> and, later, sales and marketing.<ref name=\"Gilbert\">{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Alorie|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/sizing-up-microsofts-new-windows-chief/|title=Sizing up Microsoft's new Windows chief|date=21 September 2005|accessdate=12 November 2019|publisher=CNET}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-9998192-56.html|title=Kevin Johnson to leave Microsoft for Juniper|date=July 23, 2008|publisher=CNET NEWS|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011195003/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-9998192-56.html|archive-date=October 11, 2008|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> In 2001, he led the rollout of Microsoft wireless internet in Starbucks stores,<ref name=\"Starbucks3\" /><ref name=Garnick/> which is when he met and began working with Starbucks founder Howard Schultz.<ref name=Garnick/> In 2003, Johnson was appointed group vice president of Microsoft's worldwide sales, marketing and services group.<ref name=\"cnet2\"/> As head of worldwide sales, the company's top sales post, he \"re-engineered field sales and realigned subsidiary operations\" in around 80 countries.<ref name=Gilbert/> On September 30, 2005 he was appointed co-president of Microsoft's newly created Platforms division, assuming sole responsibility after co-president Jim Allchin retired in 2006, giving Johnson responsibility over [[Windows Live]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] operating systems, [[online advertising]], search functions,<ref name=\"MSNBC\" /> servers, tools, and [[MSN]] online.<ref name=\"AP/NYT\">{{cite news |title=Microsoft Announces Major Reorganization |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/20/technology/microsoft-announces-major-reorganization.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=The New York Times |date=September 20, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"cnet2\" /> Johnson oversaw $20 billion out of Microsoft's $56 billion in revenue,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Holen |first1=Endre |title=My transition story |journal=McKinsey Quarterly |date=June 2010 |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/featured-insights/leadership/my-transition-story |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> spearheading its \"revamped online search and advertising strategy,\" regarded as crucial to competing with Google's online search tools.<ref name=\"CNET\" /> In 2006, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' named Johnson fourth on a list of \"Rising Stars\" in the technology industry.<ref name=\"Colvin\">{{cite news |last1=Colvin |first1=Geoffrey |title=The war for top talent |url=https://archive.fortune.com/2006/01/23/magazines/fortune/starintroduction_fortune_060206/index.htm |accessdate=20 November 2019 |publisher=Fortune |date=January 25, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn the Senior Leadership Team, Johnson became one of six executives along with Steve Ballmer and Bill Gates who oversaw strategy for Microsoft.<ref name=Gilbert/> Overseeing the release of Windows Vista in 2006 and 2007, in 2007 Johnson led Microsoft's acquisition of the online advertising company aQuantive for $6 billion.<ref name=MSNBC/> In 2008, he was a key figure in negotiations between Yahoo and Microsoft,<ref name=MSNBC/> with Microsoft ultimately withdrawing an acquisition offer. He resigned from Microsoft in July 2008.<ref name=\"MSNBC\" /><ref name=\"cnet2\"/>\n\n===Juniper===\nIn September 2008, Johnson became CEO of [[Juniper Networks]], in [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/windows/operatingsystems/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=209600497 |title=Microsoft Windows Exec Kevin Johnson Jumps To Juniper |date=2008-07-24 |publisher=InformationWeek |accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref><ref name=Network>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/news/2008/072508-juniper-ceo.html |title=Juniper CEO: Timing right to step aside |date=2008-07-25 |publisher=Network World |accessdate=2009-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124162146/http://www.networkworld.com/news/2008/072508-juniper-ceo.html |archivedate=2009-01-24 }}</ref><ref name=Sutton>{{cite web|url=http://www.itp.net/news/525861-kevin-johnson-signed-as-new-juniper-ceo|title=Kevin Johnson signed as new Juniper CEO |date=2008-07-25|publisher=ITP.Net|accessdate=2009-02-03|author=Sutton, Mark}}</ref><ref name=Lai>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9110561 |title=Update: Windows and online chief to leave Microsoft in wake of Yahoo tussle |date=2008-07-23 |publisher=Computerworld |accessdate=2009-02-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731170859/http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9110561 |archivedate=2008-07-31 |author=Lai, Eric}}</ref> In a statement announcing Johnson's departure from Microsoft to serve as CEO of Juniper, [[Steve Ballmer]], CEO, Microsoft, praised Johnson's contribution to the company.<ref name=MSNBC>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25823251/ns/business-us_business/t/top-online-windows-exec-depart-microsoft/#.W-XmDnpKhTY|title=Top online, Windows exec to depart Microsoft|date=2008-07-24|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en}}</ref> In July 2013, Juniper Networks announced that Johnson would step down as CEO and planned to retire. He continued to serve as CEO while a search for a new CEO was conducted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crn.com/news/networking/240158806/juniper-ceo-johnson-out-amid-q2-earnings.htm|title=Juniper CEO Johnson Out Amid Q2 Earnings|last=Bent|first=Kristin|work=CRN|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In January 2014, Johnson was succeeded as Juniper CEO by [[Shaygan Kheradpir]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Juniper Networks gets new CEO|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24516152/juniper-networks-gets-new-ceo-shaygan-kheradpir|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=2014-02-20}}</ref>\n\n===Starbucks===\n[[File:Starbuckscenter.jpg|thumb|298x298px|Johnson first joined Starbucks in 2009, serving as president and [[Chief operating officer|COO]] from 2015 to 2017. Following the resignation of [[Howard Schultz]], Johnson was appointed his successor; he has served as CEO since 2017.]]\nJohnson became president and COO of Starbucks in March 2015, remaining on its board.<ref name=LAdaily/><ref name=KOMO/> He had oversight of global operations, including the [[supply chain]] and technology supporting 21,000 stores in 66 countries.<ref name=Starbucks2/> He also oversaw online platforms<ref name=CNBC>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/30/one-year-into-starbucks-top-job-ceo-kevin-johnson-still-has-a-lot-to-prove.html|title=One year into Starbucks' top job, CEO Kevin Johnson still has a lot to prove|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=2018-03-30|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> and worked with Schultz on a five-year strategic plan for the company, released in December 2016.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Kate|title=Starbucks' new CEO tells us he'll never be Howard Schultz halehluijah- and that's great news for the brand|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/interview-with-starbucks-new-ceo-kevin-johnson-2017-4|website=Business Insider|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=2017-04-11|date=2017-04-03}}</ref> In December 2016 it was announced that [[Howard Schultz]] would step down as CEO of Starbucks, and  in April 2017 that he had personally recruited Johnson to be his successor.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGrath|first1=Maggie|title=Howard Schultz Stepping Down As Starbucks CEO|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maggiemcgrath/2016/12/01/howard-schultz-stepping-down-as-starbucks-ceo/ |website=Forbes|accessdate=2017-04-11|date=2016-12-01}}</ref> On April 3, 2017,<ref name=\"Starbucks2\" /> Johnson became the fourth CEO in Starbucks history,<ref name=\"Garnick\">{{cite news |last1=Garnick |first1=Coral |title=Starbucks expands parental leave in fight to recruit and retain workers |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2017/01/19/starbucks-parental-leave-benefits-improvement.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=Puget Sound Business Journal |date=29 January 2017}}</ref> also remaining president.<ref name=\"Tu\">{{cite news| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/starbucks/new-starbucks-ceo-aims-to-build-company-that-will-last-a-century/|title=New Starbucks CEO aims to build company that will last a century| publisher=The Seattle Times|date=3 April 2017|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> By 2018, he had implemented a number of changes, including the rollout of mobile ordering and pickup, and a global distribution deal with Nestle.<ref name=\"Gelles\">{{cite news |last1=Gelles |first1=David |title=The C.E.O. of Starbucks Isn\u2019t Leaving. Only Howard Schultz Is. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/17/business/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson.html |date=17 June 2019|accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=\"FT\">{{cite news |last1=Edgecliffe-Johnson |first1=Andrew |title=Starbucks' Kevin Johnson: taking on a founder's brand |url=https://www.ft.com/content/62e2323c-f927-11e8-af46-2022a0b02a6c |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=The Financial Times |date=9 December 2018}}</ref> For $7.15 billion, Nestle agreed to market Starbucks products outside of Starbucks stores in countries such as the US and China,<ref name=\"FT\" /> as well as use Starbucks coffee in [[Nespresso]] and [[Nescafe]] products.<ref>{{cite news |title=Starbucks and Nestl\u00e9 Form Global Coffee Alliance to Elevate and Expand Consumer Packaged Goods |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/press/2018/starbucks-and-nestle-form-global-coffee-alliance/ |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=Starbucks |date=7 May 2018}}</ref> Under Johnson, Starbucks acquired 100 percent of its East China joint venture for $1.3 billion. He also closed Teavana stores and the e-commerce unit, and sold [[Tazo]] to [[Unilever]] for $384 million.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> Analyst commentary on his first year was mixed. While he received criticism for weak sales in the United States, he was praised by ''CNBC'' for growth in China<ref name=\"CNBC\" /> and well-received by ''Bloomberg'' and ''The New York Times''.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> Media also credited Johnson with a 15 percent stock value increase between 2017 and November 2018,<ref name=\"Jargon\" /> noted as \"not far from an all-time high.\"<ref name=\"LaMonica\">{{cite news |last1=LaMonica |first1=Paul R. |title=Starbucks is doing better than ever after Howard Schultz |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/29/investing/starbucks-stock-kevin-johnson/index.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=CNN Business |date=30 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, advocates petitioned Johnson to include baristas in Starbucks paid parental leave policy,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boushey |first1=Heather|last2=Bethell|first2=Katie |title=Everyone should have a shot at paid family leave\" |url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/04/opinions/paid-family-leave-for-all-boushey-bethell/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=4 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Garnick |first1=Coral |title=Starbucks expands parental leave in fight to recruit and retain workers |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2017/01/19/starbucks-parental-leave-benefits-improvement.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |publisher=Puget Sound Business Journal |date=29 January 2017}}</ref> and Johnson announced an expanded policy in 2018.<ref name=\"CNBC\" />\n\nIn May 2018, two Black men, who were waiting for a business associate to arrive, were arrested for trespassing in a Philadelphia Starbucks, resulting in public protests and accusations of [[racial profiling]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Emily |first1=Stewart |title=Two black men were arrested in a Philadelphia Starbucks for doing nothing |url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2018/4/14/17238494/what-happened-at-starbucks-black-men-arrested-philadelphia |website=Vox |accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Prudy\" /><ref name=\"Stoonic\" /> Describing the incident as \"reprehensible\"<ref name=\"Stoonic\" /> and apologizing personally on ''Good Morning America'', Johnson met with the victims<ref name=\"Meyer\">{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Ziati |title=Starbucks CEO vows to learn from 'mistake' in racial incident |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2018/04/26/starbucks-ceo-apologizes-mistake-racial-incident/554597002/ |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=USA Today |date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> and the Philadelphia police commissioner to arrange a settlement.<ref name=\"Prudy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/prudygourguechon/2018/05/06/the-psychology-of-apology-how-did-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson-do/#6313fd2ac8d2|title=The Psychology Of Apology: How Did Starbucks' CEO Kevin Johnson Do?|first=Prudy|last=Gourguechon|publisher=|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref> Johnson was \"widely praised\" then for also closing all United States stores for racial-bias training.<ref name=\"LaMonica\" /><ref name=\"Prudy\" /><ref name=\"Meyer\" /><ref name=\"Olsen\">{{cite news |last1=Olsen |title=Starbucks to close stores for an afternoon for bias training, |url=https://www.lamonitor.com/content/starbucks-close-stores-afternoon-bias-training |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=Los Angeles Monitor |date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Pitts\">{{cite news |last1=Pitts |first1=Loenard |title=A standing ovation for the Starbucks CEO who confronted the truth about racism in America |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/leonard-pitts-jr/article209467289.html |accessdate=19 November 2019 |publisher=Miami Herald |date=April 20, 2018}}</ref> and mandating anti-[[bias]] training for management<ref name=\"Stoonic\" /><ref name=\"Meyer\" /> and new hires.<ref name=\"Gelles\" /> In 2018, Johnson opened the Tryer Center, a Seattle research laboratory, to test new product and equipment ideas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=La Roche |first1=Julia |title=How tech-savvy Kevin Johnson is creating 'the next generation' of Starbucks |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/starbucks-kevin-johnson-explains-tech-savvy-approach-161109308.html |publisher=Yahoo! finance |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Under Johnson, in 2018 and 2019, the company began developing biodegradable lids, straws, and cups,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winer-Bronner|first1=Danielle |title=Starbucks is eliminating plastic straws from all stores |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/09/news/companies/starbucks-plastic-straws/index.html |publisher=The Financial Times |date=9 July 2018|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> and partnered with UberEATS and Alibaba to deliver in the United States and China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lucas |first1=Amelia |title=Starbucks ramps up US delivery with UberEats as Chinese delivery booms |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/26/starbucks-ramps-up-us-delivery-with-ubereats-as-chinese-delivery-booms.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=CNBC}}</ref> ''The Financial Times'' reported, in 2018, that \"colleagues credit [Johnson's] tech background with helping Starbucks outpace other retailers in mobile ordering and payments.\"<ref name=\"FT\" /> He was named one of Seattle\u2019s Most Influential People of 2018 by ''Seattle Magazine'' for partnering Starbucks and Mary's Place, along with other initiatives to support homeless families.<ref name=\"Stoonic\">{{cite journal |last1=Stoonic |first1=Niki |title=Seattle\u2019s Most Influential People 2018: Starbucks CEO, Kevin Johnson |url=https://www.seattlemag.com/news-and-features/seattles-most-influential-people-2018-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson |accessdate=11 November 2019 |journal=Seattle Magazine |issue=November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, it was reported that Johnson was scaling down several of Schultz's initiatives from two years prior, including testing of Starbucks Reserve Roastery cafes. According to ''The Wall Street Journal'', that \"discipline\" had also resulted in slowed store growth in the United States, and that Johnson was \"working to improve customer service, pushing the company to develop more innovative beverages and expanding its reach in China.\"<ref name=\"Jargon\" /> Under Johnson, Starbucks shares had risen 79 percent by August 2019, and Johnson pledged to return $25 billion to shareholders by 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cannivet |first1=Michael |title=Starbucks' Big Stock Buyback Limits Future Upside |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelcannivet/2019/08/29/starbucks-big-stock-buyback-limits-future-upside/#23e9ba227047 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |publisher=Forbes |date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government work ==\nIn 2008, Johnson was appointed by [[George W. Bush]] to the National Security Telecommunications Advisory Committee (NSTAC),<ref name=\"NSTAC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/NSTAC%20Members%20-%20JohnsonK%20(Juniper%20Networks)_0.pdf|title=Committee Member Biography The President\u2019s National Security Telecommunications Advisory Committee|date=March 25, 2010|accessdate=13 November 2019|publisher=Department of Homeland Security}}</ref> where he served under Bush and [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"LAdaily\" /> As chairman of the cybersecurity committee, Johnson was tasked with proposing methods to deal with a cyber security attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nextgov.com/cybersecurity/2009/05/experts-make-push-for-cybersecurity-coordination-center/43887/|title=Experts make push for cybersecurity coordination center|last1=Noyes|first1=Andrew|date=May 22, 2009|website=Nextgov.com|publisher=Atlantic Media Co.|accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson and his wife, June, have two sons<ref name=\"ST-Tu\">{{cite news |last1=Tu |first1=Janet |title=New Starbucks CEO aims to build company that will last a century |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/starbucks/new-starbucks-ceo-aims-to-build-company-that-will-last-a-century/ |accessdate=14 November 2019 |publisher=The Seattle Times |date=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=LAdaily/> and reside in [[Medina, Washington|Medina]] and [[Bellevue, Washington]].<ref name=\"Starbucks3\">{{cite web |title=A Conversation with New Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson |url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2017/starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson/ |publisher=Starbucks |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ST-Tu\"/> Around 2012 Johnson temporarily retired from business to focus on his health, having previously diagnosed with a treatable cancer.<ref name=Starbucks3/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40509007/the-health-scare-that-revitalized-starbucks-ceo-kevin-johnson |title=The Health Scare That Revitalized Starbucks CEO Kevin Johnson|website=Fastcompany.com |publisher=Fast Company |accessdate=14 November 2019 |date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> Johnson is active in basketball, boating, golfing, skiing, and hiking.<ref name=\"ST-Tu\" /><ref name=Garnick/> A sports fan, Johnson cites writings by basketball coach [[John Wooden]] as a personal influence.<ref name=Starbucks3/>\n\nJohnson has served as an advisor to [[Catalyst (nonprofit organization)|Catalyst]], an organization dedicated to women's career advancement; is a founding board member of the [[nonprofit organization]] NPower; and supports Youth Eastside Services, and the No Child Sleeps Outside campaign.<ref name=\"ST-Tu\" /><ref name=\"Starbucks2\" /><ref name=\"Starbucks2\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of chief executive officers]]\n*[[List of New Mexico State University people|List of New Mexico State University alumni]]\n*[[Development of Windows Vista]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Juniper Networks}}\n{{Starbucks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Kevin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]] \n[[Category:Juniper Networks]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:People associated with networking industry]]\n[[Category:Directors of Starbucks]]\n[[Category:New Mexico State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Starbucks people]]\n", "name_user": "DonSpencer1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Johnson_(executive)"}
